CS-4760 Project 5: Resource Management & Deadlock Detection
============================================================
Author:      Cynthia Sims
Date:        2026-04-21
Environment: opsys.cs.umsl.edu  (Linux, gcc)


Overview
--------
Two-process system that simulates resource allocation and deadlock detection.

  oss     -- master process; manages a shared resource descriptor table,
             a simulated clock, and a System V message queue.  Forks worker
             processes, grants or queues resource requests, and runs periodic
             deadlock detection using Banker's algorithm.

  worker  -- child process; each turn randomly requests (70%) or releases
             (30%) one unit of one resource, communicates with oss via the
             message queue, and exits when its simulated time limit expires
             or oss tells it to terminate.


Files
-----
  shared.h   -- IPC keys, constants, PCB/SharedMem/Message structs
  oss.c      -- master scheduler / resource manager
  worker.c   -- child process
  Makefile   -- suffix rules; builds oss and worker
  README     -- this file


Compile
-------
  make          builds both executables
  make clean    removes object files, executables, and oss.log


Run
---
  ./oss [options]

  Options:
    -h              print help and exit
    -n proc         total number of worker processes to launch (default: 20)
    -s simul        maximum simultaneous workers (default: 5, hard cap: 18)
    -t seconds      simulated time limit per child in seconds (default: 3)
    -i ms           simulated milliseconds between worker launches (default: 100)
    -f logfile      log file path (default: oss.log)

  Examples:
    ./oss -n 5 -s 3 -t 5 -f test.log
    ./oss -n 20 -s 18 -t 2
    ./oss -h

  Termination:
    oss stops forking after -n total workers have been launched or after
    5 real-time seconds, whichever comes first.  A SIGALRM fires after
    30 real-time seconds as a hard deadline.  Ctrl-C (SIGINT) also triggers
    a clean shutdown.  In all cases oss kills remaining children, frees IPC
    resources, and prints final statistics.


IPC Resources
-------------
  Shared memory key:  0x47605  (one segment: SimClock + PCB table + resource tables)
  Message queue key:  0x47606

  If the program exits uncleanly, check for leftover IPC with:
    ipcs -m
    ipcs -q
  and remove them with:
    ipcrm -m <shmid>
    ipcrm -q <msgid>


Design Notes
------------
Resource table
  10 resource classes, 5 instances each (50 total).
  oss tracks available[], allocation[process][resource], and
  request[process][resource] (1 if blocked waiting for that resource).
  Workers only read the simulated clock from shared memory; all allocation
  data is managed exclusively by oss.

Message protocol
  Worker to oss: mtype = 1, msg_action = MSG_REQUEST / MSG_RELEASE / MSG_TERMINATE
    mvalue > 0  -- request one unit of resource (mvalue - 1)
    mvalue < 0  -- release one unit of resource (-mvalue - 1)
    mvalue = 0  -- terminate acknowledgment
  Oss to worker: mtype = worker_pid, msg_action = MSG_TURN / MSG_GRANT / MSG_TERMINATE

Blocked processes
  When a request cannot be granted, oss adds the worker to a per-resource
  FIFO wait queue and sends NO reply; the worker stays blocked in msgrcv.
  When another process releases that resource, oss dequeues and grants the
  first waiter by sending a MSG_GRANT.

Deadlock detection (every 1 simulated second)
  Implements the resource-allocation-graph reduction variant of Banker's
  algorithm (detection mode, not avoidance):
    1. Work[] = available[]
    2. Finish[i] = false for every occupied PCB slot
    3. Find i where Finish[i]==false and request[i] <= Work
    4. If found: Work += allocation[i]; Finish[i] = true; goto 3
    5. Any Finish[i]==false => deadlocked
  oss terminates one victim from the deadlocked set, frees its resources
  (which may unblock other processes), then re-runs detection.

Simulated clock
  Advances 1:1 with real wall time using CLOCK_MONOTONIC.  Each
  main-loop iteration measures the actual elapsed nanoseconds since the
  previous call and adds that amount to the sim clock (capped at 1 s to
  guard against large scheduler preemptions).  CLOCK_INC_NS (10 ms) is
  retained as a reference constant but is not used at runtime.
  Only oss writes; workers read to check their time limit.

Logging
  Output goes to both stdout and the log file.  Writing stops after 10,000
  lines to prevent runaway files.  Worker output does NOT go to the log.
  A resource table is printed every 0.5 simulated seconds.
  Final statistics (total requests, immediate-grant percentage, deadlock
  detection runs, and deadlock kills) are printed at the end of every run.


Generative AI Usage
-------------------
Claude Code (claude.ai/code) was used to assist with the design and
implementation of this project, including struct layout, IPC boilerplate,
and the deadlock-detection loop.  All code was reviewed and verified by
the author.  Use disclosed per course policy.
